	abstract = {The polar headgroups are an important molecular subregion of phospholipids since they mediate a substantial part of the interactions emerging with other constituents of biological membranes, be it inherent macromolecules (proteins) or water as forming the natural environment. FTIR spectroscopy is well proven for characterizing aspects of weak interactions, above all hydrogen bonding. We have used this method to study solid deposits of a number of selected lipid models, such as choline, acetylcholine and methylphosphocholine (MePC), and compared them with the common phospholipid dimyristoylglycerophosphocholine (DMPC), at different degrees of hydration, which were varied via relative humidity (RH).
